        "id": 1002134
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-11T06:47:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think the two zeros serve different purposes.\nThe network parameter here comes directly from the kernel when receiving an MCTP packet, and the kernel is expected to fill in the actual device network ID, so 0 shouldn\u0027t appear there.\nThe MCTP_NET_ANY fallback searches stored tid_map entries where map_tid() stores entries with net \u003d 0 to mean \"match any network.\"\nSame numeric value, different layers.\n@vishnunithyasoundhar.s@intel.com might be able to provide more context since the original network !\u003d 0 guard was introduced in [6b8f264].\n\n[6b8f264]: https://github.com/openbmc/libpldm/commit/6b8f2646bc2abbeb7ccb074aa23fb7be929d1f00#diff-1dde80e9a2b9e2874a0aabde1a857d18252904d9c17c31968e4e785836cd3ea4",
      "parentUuid": "92c4a1cd_28d62099",
      "revId": "e068f8802e07e730ae57f0f59f1679d679741202",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "75ad0cc2_f5879dfd",
        "filename": "src/transport/af-mctp.c",
        "patchSetId": 30
      },
      "lineNbr": 81,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002607
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-11T09:51:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "https://github.com/openbmc/libpldm/blob/80cde632088394b9b3da90cf677b8d2763278c77/src/transport/af-mctp.c#L170\n\nIn the linked code, this is the point where we obtain the network value that is later passed to pldm_transport_af_mctp_get_tid. The value comes directly from the kernel MCTP socket, which always provides a valid MCTP link identifier—however, MCTP link IDs are never allowed to be 0.\nTherefore, a net \u003d 0 value cannot represent a valid MCTP network.\n\nIn scenarios where someone previously used the old API to map a TID:\n\nThe network would typically be 1, since that is the default MCTP link ID.\nA call to find_tid(..., network, ...) would fail because it would not find a mapping associated with network 1.\nA call to find_tid(..., MCTP_NET_ANY, ...) would succeed, assuming the old-API-based mapping still exists, because it searches across all networks.",
      "parentUuid": "fd8c382b_a603f6b9",
      "revId": "e068f8802e07e730ae57f0f59f1679d679741202",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
